# Solo Workflow — SQLite, no PG

> **Project:** {{ .ProjectPrefix }}
> **Generated by:** mtix {{ .Version }}
> **Workflow audience:** individual contributors, pre-team adoption.

> **Trust banner.** BYO PG = trusted team sharing one database. NOT a
> multi-tenant boundary. Anyone with PG write access can read/modify all
> task data. This solo workflow does not use BYO PG, but the same trust
> assumption applies the moment you switch to it.

This is the default mtix mode. One developer, one machine, one SQLite
database under `.mtix/data/mtix.db`. Sync between machines (your laptop
and your desktop, say) is via the git-tracked `.mtix/tasks.json` snapshot.

You should pick this workflow if you are a single developer or
evaluating mtix before bringing a team in. When you add even one
collaborator who needs to mutate tasks, move to the
[small-team workflow](small-team.md) — concurrent SQLite writers across
machines is not a supported topology.

---

## Setup steps

1. Install mtix: `go install github.com/hyper-swe/mtix/cmd/mtix@latest`.
2. Initialize the project from your repo root: `mtix init`. This creates
   `.mtix/data/mtix.db` and the documentation set.
3. Verify `.mtix/data/` is **not** in `.gitignore`. SQLite is tracked
   alongside the snapshot file so a fresh clone has a working store.
4. Create your first task: `mtix create --title "Bootstrap the codebase"`.
5. Optional: install the bundled Claude Code skills with
   `mtix plugin install claude-code` so your IDE agent picks them up.

---

## Failure modes

| What can go wrong | How mtix behaves | What you do |
|---|---|---|
| `.mtix/data/mtix.db` corrupted | Read/write fails with a clear error | Restore from `.mtix/tasks.json` via `mtix import`; commit a fresh snapshot |
| Two agents on same machine race a write | SQLite WAL + busy_timeout serialize writes | No action; this is the supported concurrent topology for solo mode |
| PG unreachable | N/A — solo mode does not use PG | Switch to small-team workflow before adding remote collaborators |
| Pre-push hook bypassed (`git push --no-verify`) | tasks.json may lag the DB | Re-export with `mtix export` and commit |
| Schema mismatch after upgrade | Startup migration runs automatically; failure aborts | `mtix verify`, then re-run; report a bug if migration loops |
| `audit_log` full | N/A — `audit_log` is a BYO PG feature | Not applicable to solo mode |
| Two devs push simultaneously | Git rejects the second push as non-fast-forward | Pull, re-export, push again |
| Network partition mid-push | Git push fails; local state intact | Retry once the network is back |

---

## Trust boundary

**What this workflow protects against:**

- Local data loss — `.mtix/tasks.json` snapshot in git history is your DR.
- Concurrent agent corruption on one machine — SQLite WAL handles it.
- SQL injection in filter inputs — all queries are parameterized.

**What this workflow does NOT protect against:**

- A teammate concurrently editing the same SQLite file from another
  machine — solo mode is single-machine. Use small-team for that.
- Loss of your laptop without a recent push — the `.mtix/tasks.json`
  in git is your only off-machine copy.
- Tampering with the local SQLite file by anything running on your
  machine. Solo mode trusts the local machine fully.

---

## Disaster recovery

Solo DR is git-driven and intentionally minimal:

1. Clone the repo to a new machine.
2. Run `mtix init` if `.mtix/data/mtix.db` is missing.
3. Run `mtix import .mtix/tasks.json` to rebuild the SQLite store from
   the last committed snapshot.
4. Verify with `mtix list --status open`.

For richer DR (point-in-time recovery, audit log replay), see the
[safety-critical workflow](safety-critical.md), which uses BYO PG and
documents the full restore procedure.

